{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-note-template-js","path":"/vintage radio bluetooth speakers/","result":{"pageContext":{"id":"d893b704-fd92-587f-b38e-79064a03c32f","html":"<h1>vintage radio bluetooth speakers</h1>\n<p><em>may 2026</em></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/581d39e11e121c4b1fe4e6a42627b68d/d3c45/radio-wip.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 133.1081081081081%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"an old transistor radio with a bluetooth speaker soldered in\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/581d39e11e121c4b1fe4e6a42627b68d/1c72d/radio-wip.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/581d39e11e121c4b1fe4e6a42627b68d/a80bd/radio-wip.jpg 148w,\n/static/581d39e11e121c4b1fe4e6a42627b68d/1c91a/radio-wip.jpg 295w,\n/static/581d39e11e121c4b1fe4e6a42627b68d/1c72d/radio-wip.jpg 590w,\n/static/581d39e11e121c4b1fe4e6a42627b68d/a8a14/radio-wip.jpg 885w,\n/static/581d39e11e121c4b1fe4e6a42627b68d/fbd2c/radio-wip.jpg 1180w,\n/static/581d39e11e121c4b1fe4e6a42627b68d/d3c45/radio-wip.jpg 3472w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>i found a cheap transistor radio at goodwill for $6, and thought, \"i could make a speaker out of this!\"</p>\n<p>so i did. eventually. it was several months before i got around to buying the soldering iron.</p>\n<p>but all i needed to do was:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>strip out the existing electronics, leaving only the speaker wire (this does mean it is no longer a radio, but it's much easier to do)</li>\n<li>buy the cheapest bluetooth speaker i can find from amazon (i went with <a href=\"\">this one</a>) and rip the speaker off, leaving everything else on the board intact.</li>\n<li>red to red, black to black.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>and it worked! it has a nice vintage sound that is fun to put on in the background. i was so pleased i bought two more little radios on ebay and two more speakers, and now i have three! these new ones pictured atop my dust collector.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/5f452cdacf52c64360f0e0bbda57314a/d3c45/radios-collection.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 133.1081081081081%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"three vintage radios atop a red cube\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/5f452cdacf52c64360f0e0bbda57314a/1c72d/radios-collection.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/5f452cdacf52c64360f0e0bbda57314a/a80bd/radios-collection.jpg 148w,\n/static/5f452cdacf52c64360f0e0bbda57314a/1c91a/radios-collection.jpg 295w,\n/static/5f452cdacf52c64360f0e0bbda57314a/1c72d/radios-collection.jpg 590w,\n/static/5f452cdacf52c64360f0e0bbda57314a/a8a14/radios-collection.jpg 885w,\n/static/5f452cdacf52c64360f0e0bbda57314a/fbd2c/radios-collection.jpg 1180w,\n/static/5f452cdacf52c64360f0e0bbda57314a/d3c45/radios-collection.jpg 3472w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>"}},"staticQueryHashes":[],"slicesMap":{}}